
1. Why is visualization important after training an ML model?

Visualization transforms abstract metrics into actionable insights by revealing patterns, biases, and failure modes that scalar metrics (R², accuracy) conceal. Essential for model validation, debugging, and stakeholder communication.

Engineering Impact Metrics:

text
Scalar metrics: R²=0.82 → "Model is good"
Visual diagnostics: Residual funnel shape → "Heteroscedasticity detected"
Stakeholder trust: Numbers → Charts → Executive buy-in (3x faster)

Primary Use Cases:

    Overfitting detection (training vs validation curves)

    Feature importance (business prioritization)

    Error patterns (systematic bias identification)

    Outlier diagnosis (data quality issues)



2. What types of ML outputs can be shown in Streamlit?

Streamlit supports all major ML outputs natively:

| ML Output Type     | Streamlit Function              | Example                |
| ------------------ | ------------------------------- | ---------------------- |
| Predictions        | st.metric(), st.line_chart()    | Salary forecasts       |
| Confusion Matrix   | px.imshow(cm)                   | Classification errors  |
| Feature Importance | px.bar(coef_df)                 | Variable impact        |
| Residuals          | px.scatter(pred, residuals)     | Error patterns         |
| ROC Curves         | px.line(fpr, tpr)               | Classifier performance |
| Learning Curves    | px.line(train_score, val_score) | Overfitting detection  |

